{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658585"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:51:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:51:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20781"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20781"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.08,0,0.08,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13656"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95964"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13656"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20781"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78704"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"11717"},{"type":"tags","id":"12629"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32866"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32867"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95964"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECytomegalovirus (CMV) is a common herpesvirus that can cause significant morbidity in immunocompromised patients. The virus has developed sophisticated mechanisms to evade and suppress host immune responses.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how CMV evades the immune system?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Down-modulates MHC class I and II molecules","Induces apoptosis of all T lymphocytes","Permanently destroys dendritic cells","Blocks all cytokine production","Prevents antibody production completely"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECMV effectively evades immune detection by \u003Cstrong\u003Edown-modulating MHC class I and II molecules\u003C/strong\u003E on infected cells. This prevents recognition by both CD8+ and CD4+ T cells, allowing the virus to avoid detection by adaptive immunity. Additionally, CMV produces homologues of TNF receptor superfamily members, IL-10, and class I MHC molecules that further interfere with immune recognition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInduces apoptosis of all T lymphocytes\u003C/strong\u003E - While CMV causes immunosuppression, it does not induce widespread T cell apoptosis. In fact, CD8+ and CD4+ T cell responses are crucial for controlling CMV infection.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPermanently destroys dendritic cells\u003C/strong\u003E - CMV infects dendritic cells and impairs their function in antigen processing and T cell stimulation, but does not permanently destroy them.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks all cytokine production\u003C/strong\u003E - CMV modulates cytokine responses rather than blocking all cytokine production. It actually produces homologues of certain cytokines like IL-10 to manipulate the immune response.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents antibody production completely\u003C/strong\u003E - CMV encodes Fc\u03b3-binding glycoproteins that interfere with IgG-mediated immunity, but it does not completely prevent antibody production.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECMV employs multiple strategies to evade immune detection, including interfering with natural killer (NK) cell function by producing ligands that block activating receptors and class I-like proteins that engage inhibitory receptors. The virus also impairs dendritic cell function, affecting antigen presentation and T cell stimulation. Despite these evasion mechanisms, CD8+ T cells, CD4+ T cells, \u03b3\u03b4 T cells, and NK cells all play important roles in controlling CMV infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cytomegalovirus (CMV) evades immune detection by down-modulating major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules and producing homologues of immune signaling proteins.","CMV infection causes transient but severe immunosuppression by impairing dendritic cell function and antigen presentation.","Multiple immune cell types including CD8+ T cells, CD4+ T cells, \u03b3\u03b4 T cells, and natural killer cells contribute to controlling CMV infection."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; page 356."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78704"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20781"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78704"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-30T13:36:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-30T13:38:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13656"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95964"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":7,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:04:44+10:30","u